metadata.name: Endless Braids #60
metadata.description:
This generative braid artwork is built in plain JavaScript, and is based on code I wrote several years ago, here updated with new aesthetics and features. This work is motivated by a beautiful mathematical structure called a braid group.

Each unique mint of the token chooses randomized parameters with varying probability weights for the number of strings, their spacing, coloring schemes and resulting color palettes, and crossing sizes, angles and frequency.

Colors are randomly generated from an algorithm, including the background color. Most of the pieces (70% probability) will feature colors from two separate hue intervals; a smaller number (20%) use only one color interval, and even more rare are the Black-White-Color palettes (6%), and the Black-and-White palette (4%).

Most of them scroll up, but approximately 7% of them scroll down.

The braid will endlessly scroll without any repetition in its pattern.

Dan Gries
Twitter: @rectangleworld

metadata.name: glory hole$ #356
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: One Tezo Drawings_114+ #30
metadata.description:
The One Tezo Drawings project is a variation of the âDesenhos de um Realâ project (2006- ). In it, the artist sets the price of his work by making a rational calculation, equating his artistic production with a consumer good detached from the art world .
In this case, the calculation is based on the amount charged per hour of work from the minimum wage in the United States. Thus, a drawing that took X hours to produce (Wt) will have its price fixed at USD 15.00 * Wt divided by the value in Dollars of one Tezo (Dt) at the time of publication. But for the final price to be 1.00 Tez, the total production time value (Wt) will be divided by the number of editions (Ed). Therefore, the number of editions is defined by the following formula: 1.00 Tez = (Wt*15/Dt)/Ed ==> 

Ed=Wt*15/Dt 

For this particular project:
Permutation of 10 to 16 mirrored layers.

Wt= 9.75
Dt= 2.14
Ed= 9.75*15/2.14 = 68

Press J or P to save a 1500x1500px image

metadata.name: Idem Locus #13
metadata.description:
The artist of this art piece found its inspiration not in an individual artist, but rather in the aesthetic of an entire era - the engravings from the Late Middle Ages and the early Renaissance.

"Idem Locus" (Latin for "The Same Place") was conceived as a result of delving into the engravings of the 15th and 16th centuries, contrasting the portrayed locations with their contemporary counterparts. 

Idem Locus was part of the Blind Gallery x Feral File Vistas Edition
For more information, visit https://www.blindgallery.xyz/

metadata.name: ecologÃ­as - B #989
metadata.description:
ecologÃ­as - B

water is the medium where life first appeared in our planet. Water is also indispensable for the continuation of the life that emerged from - and with - it. The advent of AI species and their introduction into society is a new form of cambrian explosion. What is their medium? What is their water? How scarce and precious will it be for them? AI entities are not foreign to human resource necessities, though. The water that is essential to our human life will also be so for machines, as their energy still depends on our natural resources. Therefore, the ecologies of humans and machines will have, at least, the same elements as the ecologies of humans. AIs may help us reach better balances, only if we employ them to do so and if we teach them to help us.

ecologÃ­as-B is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecologÃ­as A and ecologÃ­as C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, @msoriaro

press s to save current image in current resolution
press z,x,g,b,n followed by +/- to increase/decrease, respectively, brightness, contrast, gamma, blur, noise
press l (as in loop) to pause/resume the piece

metadata.name: Reading a book #3
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Absorbed #463
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEFâs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MATâ¢). 

MATâ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MATâ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed â high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and âsinusoidalâ noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artistsâ belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphicaâs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: Cosmic Poems #287
metadata.description:
Cosmic Poems is the fourth iteration of my work that explores the algorithmic space of typography. In this new piece, I expand on my initial inspirations of the early concrete poetry movement bringing in texts of my own. These short texts are taken from my extensive notes on the subject of artificial intelligence. Snippets of plausible pistes of reflection as well as lighter more tongue in cheek ideas make up the selection I have curated for the work. I hope that it may engage your attention with pleasure.
